The paper deals with algorithms for answering conjunctive queries with negation, which is a topic in database theory (cs.DB) and computational complexity (cs.CC). The use of hypertree width and submodular width also suggests a connection to algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also introduces a generalization of the color-coding technique, which is a popular randomized algorithm in theoretical computer science and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper's focus on query rewriting and tensor decomposition suggests a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
